{
  "text": "While the availability of cheap range sensors like Kinect makes large-scale supervised training of single-view depth and normal predictions possible for indoor scenes, the absence of high quality, dense depth sensing outdoors makes supervised learning difficult. To address this problem, Garg et al. [CITATION_1] introduced a self-supervised learning paradigm where large stereo data-set can be used to train the single view depth prediction networks by using the traditional dense stereo loss function of [CITATION_2] as the supervisory signal. Various extensions of the self-supervised learning for depth estimation have been proposed in recent times, including the use of robust image alignment costs, Godard et al. [CITATION_3] . [CITATION_4] extended the framework to enable training depth predictors using monocular sequence whereas [CITATION_5] , [CITATION_6] advocate using stereo sequences to train a network for unsupervised two-frame visual odometry, because this addresses the issue of metric scale (which is otherwise unobservable). [CITATION_7] additionally propose to learn good features to match and [CITATION_8] advocate to evaluate the quality of warp using Generative Adversarial Networks [CITATION_9] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "299085",
    "[CITATION_2]": "1371968",
